.SH SHMTVarOpt
Calculate the theoretical minimum variance of a localized multitaper
spectral estimate and the corresponding optimal weights to apply to each
localized spectrum.
.SH Usage
call SHMTVarOpt (\f[CR]l\f[R], \f[CR]tapers\f[R],
\f[CR]taper_order\f[R], \f[CR]lwin\f[R], \f[CR]kmax\f[R],
\f[CR]sff\f[R], \f[CR]var_opt\f[R], \f[CR]var_unit\f[R],
\f[CR]weight_opt\f[R], \f[CR]unweighted_covar\f[R], \f[CR]nocross\f[R],
\f[CR]exitstatus\f[R])
.SH Parameters
.TP
\f[CR]l\f[R] : input, integer
The spherical harmonic used degree to determine the minimum variance and
optimal weights.
.TP
\f[CR]tapers\f[R] : input, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]lwin\f[R]+1, \f[CR]kmax\f[R])
A matrix of localization functions obtained from
\f[CR]SHReturnTapers\f[R] or \f[CR]SHReturnTapersM\f[R].
.TP
\f[CR]taper_order\f[R] : input, integer(int32), dimension (\f[CR]kmax\f[R])
The angular order of the windowing coefficients in \f[CR]tapers\f[R].
.TP
\f[CR]lwin\f[R] : input, integer(int32)
The spherical harmonic bandwidth of the localizing windows.
.TP
\f[CR]kmax\f[R] : input, integer(int32)
The maximum number of tapers to be used when calculating the minimum
variance and optimal weights.
.TP
\f[CR]sff\f[R] : input, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]l\f[R]+\f[CR]lwin\f[R]+1)
The global unwindowed power spectrum of the function to be localized.
.TP
\f[CR]var_opt\f[R] : output, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]kmax\f[R])
The minimum variance of the multitaper spectral estimate for degree
\f[CR]l\f[R] using 1 through \f[CR]kmax\f[R] tapers.
.TP
\f[CR]var_unit\f[R] : output, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]kmax\f[R])
The variance of the multitaper spectral estimate using equal weights for
degree \f[CR]l\f[R] using 1 through \f[CR]kmax\f[R] tapers.
.TP
\f[CR]weight_opt\f[R] : optional, output, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]kmax\f[R], \f[CR]kmax\f[R])
The optimal weights (in columns) that minimize the multitaper spectral
estimate\(cqs variance using 1 through \f[CR]kmax\f[R] tapers.
.TP
\f[CR]unweighted_covar\f[R] : optional, output, real(dp), dimension (\f[CR]kmax\f[R], \f[CR]kmax\f[R])
The unweighted covariance matrix of the \f[CR]kmax\f[R] tapers (i.e.,
Fij in Wieczorek and Simons 2007).
.TP
\f[CR]nocross\f[R] : optional, input, integer(int32), default = 0
If 1, only the diagonal terms of the covariance matrix Fij will be
computed.
If 0, all terms will be computed.
.TP
\f[CR]exitstatus\f[R] : output, optional, integer(int32)
If present, instead of executing a STOP when an error is encountered,
the variable exitstatus will be returned describing the error.
0 = No errors; 1 = Improper dimensions of input array; 2 = Improper
bounds for input variable; 3 = Error allocating memory; 4 = File IO
error.
.SH Description
\f[CR]SHMTVarOpt\f[R] will determine the minimum variance that can be
achieved by a weighted multitaper spectral analysis, as is described by
Wieczorek and Simons (2007).
The minimum variance is output as a function of the number of tapers
utilized, from 1 to a maximum of \f[CR]kmax\f[R], and the corresponding
variance using equal weights is output for comparison.
The windowing functions are assumed to be solutions to the
spherical\-cap concentration problem, as determined by a call to
\f[CR]SHReturnTapers\f[R] or \f[CR]SHReturnTapersM\f[R].
The minimum variance and weights are dependent upon the form of the
global unwindowed power spectrum, \f[CR]Sff\f[R].
.PP
If the optional argument \f[CR]weight_opt\f[R] is specified, then the
optimal weights will be returned as a function of the number of tapers
employed, from 1 to \f[CR]kmax\f[R].
If \f[CR]unweighted_covar\f[R] is specified, then the unweighted
covariance matrix of the \f[CR]kmax\f[R] tapers (i.e., Fij) will be
output.
If the optional argument \f[CR]nocross\f[R] is set to 1, then only the
diagnonal terms of \f[CR]Fij\f[R] will be computed.
.SH References
Wieczorek, M. A. and F. J. Simons, Minimum\-variance multitaper spectral
estimation on the sphere, J. Fourier Anal.
Appl., 13, doi:10.1007/s00041\-006\-6904\-1, 665\-692, 2007.
